Parliament has not ratified the amendment for the release of Tymosenko
The Ukrainian parliament refused, as part of an amendment to criminal law, the proposed annulment of the paragraph relating to the indictment of Julia Tymosenko, the leader of the opposition.
At second reading, MEPs rejected the proposed amendment to reduce the penalties for economic offences, which could have opened the doors of freedom for the former Prime Minister currently imprisoned.
Tymosenko was sentenced in October to 7 years in prison for having concluded a pre-disadvantaged deal with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The judgement is not final and the court must rule on the appeal of the convicted person in December.
Tymosenko described the ruling as political revenge of the regime and provoked a process of suspicions of bias of the court also to the west.
The plan to annul paragraph 365 of the criminal law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was signed by 147 deputies.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve.
