The diet of an obese child: does not have breakfast and takes charcuterie for dinner
More than a third of children aged 9-13 have overweight problems, 9% of school children are above average and 5% are obese.
As current research shows, obese children come from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
This again shows how important it is to the environment in which the human being and the models around him evolves.
On the tables of obese children, for example, there are 50 per cent charcuterie more often than in families of children with normal weight.
19% of obese people had fries at dinner according to the survey conducted with an awareness-raising action "Obesity is no accident"
In families of fat kids sport is also not a habit, which is now the case for most of today's schoolchildren - only 15% responded that at least once a week parents found time for active movement.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted during the last school year and involved 900 students from primary schools in Czech Republic.
It was the second edition of "Obesity is not a chance", supported by General Health Insurance and Unilever.
Since the beginning, more than 12,000 students from sixth to third have enrolled in this project.
One of the determining factors that causes a dramatic increase in the number of overweight or even obese children is the lack of proper nutrition and not enough physical exercise.
"Only half of the children questioned indicate for example eating 5 times a day breakfast-in case - lunch - snack-dinner, which is one of the basic principles of a good diet", indicates one of the results of the survey.
Breakfast and charcuterie free at dinner
Specialists draw attention to the fact that healthy development requires some basic details such as a family breakfast at the same time.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of the students' families eat at the same time.
In most families each has breakfast alone.
And the worst thing that's been noted is that a tenth of the population doesn't have breakfast at all.
Breakfast, however, is the basis for a good daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that the families of obese children consume unhealthy fries more often.
Almost every student - not to mention weight - drinks sweet drinks every day (70%).
More than 40% of the children questioned do sports regularly but for parents this is half, only 15%.
Get ready for your diet
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own diet based on opportunities offered according to their own taste and personal opinion.
"The preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 years are far from healthy eating, ideal".
Among their favorite dishes are a lot of cakes, meats and sweets.
"The most alarming is in particular a great preference for sweet lemonade", is indicated in the survey results.
For lunch it was the pasta that took the first place right in front of the white meat.
Children did not want starch at all and the preference for fish and vegetable meals was very low.
Focus on health
The survey also showed that children are ready to change their habits from the moment they receive the ad hoc information.
"During a review of a group of survey participants who had completed the questionnaire after the awareness-raising session "Obesity is not a coincidence", there was a strong desire to move towards a healthy diet," the results of the survey indicate.
The most notable was, for example, in the case of sweet lemonade, as children have begun to give preference to drinking water.
Children most often checked white meat and fish as the main dish on the questionnaire and would reduce sweet dishes and "knedliky" (Czech speciality of bread or potato flour pellets).
