IBM History: From cheese slices to flights in the cosmos.
IBM (International Business Machines) was born in New York a hundred years ago; it initially had the complicated name of Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM in 1924 - originally a brand used by a branch of a firm in Canada and South America.
The foundation of the future IBM was the merger of four firms whose history is related to the 1980s of the nineteenth century.
They had technologies such as old "pointers", pendulums that recorded the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was Charles Ranlett Flint who until 1930 presided over the Supervisory Board of the company.
Flint hired the head of a competing firm Thomas J. Watson to help him run the company.
The leader then cast a shadow on the founder of the firm - it is Watson's ideas that so far underpin the identity and culture of society.
Watson ran the Kusqu firm in 1952.
IBM, as its name says, began with the production of all possible machines for business and commerce - from cheese and meat slicers to cash registers.
In the first four years of Watson's leadership, revenues increased to $9 million and began the firm's expansion in all parts of the world.
Watson was so irreplaceable to the firm that after 40 years of management it was his son who occupied the director's chair, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership IBM began the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM's people and computers helped NASA guide flights in the cosmos - on Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the flight on the Moon.
Meanwhile in 1964 IBM developed the first computer family - the IBM System/360.
The classic PC that determined the computer standard of the time with the name IBM 5150 arrived on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later IBM sold its computer factory to the Chinese company Lenovo, but bought the consulting company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to deal with consulting and services with high added value.
The strategy that has succeeded at IBM over the last three years - is the Smarter Planet concept "a smarter planet".
Its objective is the intelligent use of technology in areas not yet exploited, such as transport and city management.
As far as the field of trade is concerned, IBM recently developed a platform called "Smarter Commerce" which helps traders manage the entire business cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in our territory.
It established its branch in Czechoslovakia in 1932, then the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, besides IBM RT, there is also the strategic outsourcing center of Brno.
The Central for Central and Eastern Europe is based in Prague and there is also the research and development team at the global level that deals with the recognition of speech.
