Peter Englund's new book offers depth and generosity. Titled "The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War", it begins with a long list of characters that hold your heart.
A tip to start with: carefully tear this page and make it your mark-up.
You will get to know these people in detail. In this romantic narrative of Peter Englund, this list of characters will be your GPS, a beacon during these few moments when, like one of his men or women, you will be troubled and desperate in the mists of war.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which delivers the Nobel Prize in Literature.
He wrote here an unusual book which he accurately describes as "an anti-history book."
It has some known names, important treaties or famous battles; there is almost no ambassador or discussion of strategies and material.
It's not so much a book about what happened, he explains, as a "book describing what it might look like." It contains "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods."
"Beauty and grief" sums up the wartime experiences of 20 more or less ordinary men and women, on both sides of the war, from young schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, paramedics and vendors.
Some of them will become heroes.
Others are prisoners of war, some will lose limbs, go mad or lose their lives.
Their lives are flickering here like the candles of a church: while some are extinguishing, new ones are rekindled.
Peter Englund's book deviates from traditional history books.
He refuted the idea that World War I was summed up only by the terrible trench war on the western front.
"Beauty and sorrow" skilfully describes other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia and East Africa.
The soldiers present in this book are under hives; one spends Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; tsetse flies are an intractable problem.
This book is moving from the first page.
War invades the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like a hurricane Katrina that stinks of cordite.
When gunshots ring in the distance, and you are a mother at home, do you stay or flee?
Who will come anyway?
Almost no one can understand what happened, or even the reasons for this war.
According to Peter Englund, "the lack of facts has been compounded by assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumours."
"Beauty and sorrow" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, as well as Richard Stumpf, a young sailor in the German high seas fleet.
Their stories are mainly drawn from memoirs, letters and other documents already published.
The versions of their lives can be terrifying or exciting, but are most preserved thanks to the accumulation of small moments and isolated details.
Most deal with deprivation and the ability to get away with it.
In telling the story of a German schoolgirl, Peter Englund writes: "Ersatz, everywhere ersatz."
"Replacement coffee, fake aluminum, rubber imitation, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
He continues on substitute food in Germany.
It describes "meat made of cooked rice crushed in sheep fat (and finished with a fake wooden bone); tobacco made with dry roots and dried potato skin; wooden shoe soles."
He states that "837 authorized substitute meats are registered in the production of sausages. There are also 511 substitute coffees."
Some stories address honour and courage.
An American recognizes his own drive toward savagery and states about the war: "You feel that after all, that's what men were meant to do, rather than sit in a comfortable armchair, a cigarette and a whiskey in hand, reading a newspaper or a bestseller, and rather than pretending that such a varnish is synonymous with civilization, and that there is no barbaric behind your tweaked and studded shirt.
Conversely, a British soldier realizes that he is likely to die, and that no one will notice or pay attention to him.
"When one is resigned to sacrifice oneself, one hopes to have an audience," he writes.
It is unfortunately rather comparable to "a man sentenced to strangled in secret".
