2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of government of Mario López Valdez, self-called of the change, which has generated great expectations regarding the advances of the economy, but given the climatic adversity of the beginning of the year, the increase does not occur, in exchange there is a deterioration of the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures of February, apart from causing trillion losses to the agricultural sector, limited the possibilities of the state economy for growth, caused a contraction in economic activity in general by 3.6 per cent in the first half of the year, mainly justified by the historical decline of 31.16 per cent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of other economic sectors.
According to the Jelly Allocation Report of the Mexican Sustainable Rural Development Council, there was damage of 582 million 835 hectares cultivated, of which 78.03 per cent suffered total damage and the remainder of 21.07 per cent suffered partial damage, the main crops affected were vegetables, maize and chickpeas.
The decline in economic activity led, until November, to a steady increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the state unemployment rate during the first three quarters of the year was observed to increase rapidly, since while from January to March 55 thousand 053 Sinaloans were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53% of the economically active population, in the second quarter the rate became 5.28 percent and from July to September the average continued to rise until 6.19 percent, a rate that represents more than 74 thousand Sinaloans unemployed, an increase from the first half of 18 thousand 969 people.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, according to economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly according to the actions carried out by public policy.
"What we see is an increase in unemployment that is due to various factors, among which the loss of liquidity in the market due to a restriction of resources by the legislation approved in Congress to combat money laundering, because for people who earn dollars in an illicit way it is not easy for them to work to earn them, to invest them and to use them in something," he says.
Detained migration
López Cervantes reported that the rise in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
"The number of people who drop out of the state to go to work abroad, in the United States has been limited, first because of entry difficulties and secondly because when they come in they already have a lot of difficulties to find work, these people stay here and ask for sources of work, which causes unemployment to rise," he said.
Lack of seriousness
The analysis of the Sinaloen labour market is worsening by considering the high level of lack of seriousness that predominates between working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 per cent of the population employed in this state works there without contributing as a worker at any social insurance institution.
Apart from unemployment and lack of seriousness, another reason for lag for the state is low wages, the entity has the lowest wages in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Labour and Social Forecasting.
The average monthly income of Sinaloan workers was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, well below the national average of 7 thousand 375 pesos.
Contravention of FDI
Apart from the decline in economic activity and the rise in unemployment, in 2011 there was the largest reduction in Foreign Direct Investment in the last 10 years, according to the Economic Secretariat from January to June the state FDI reached 630 thousand 697 dollars, which represents a decrease of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 million 143 thousand 312 dollars recorded in the same period of the previous year.
In turn, the Economic Development Secretariat of the Government of the State accounts for a total investment of 17,280 trillion pesos per year, mainly recorded by companies in the service sector.
Debt
In view of the scenario of economic contraction, the Government of the State sought in July the approval of a loan of 3 trillion pesos for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the aim of reviving the economy, the approval of the State Congress was 2.600 trillion pesos and until November no debt benefits were observed in any sector of the State economy.
Reactions
For representatives of the employers' sector, Mario López Valdés' first year of government demonstrated a lack of government management capacity.
Miguel Loredo López, President of the National Chamber of Transformation Industry, said that in 2011 there was no harmonization of the wills of the different sectors, including the Government of the State.
"The performance of Sinaloa's economy during this year has been really very poor, we have to work intensively to recover the ground we lost this year, in 2012 we have to double our efforts, we have had to align everyone's effort and above all the good already synchronized march of this new government team, hopefully next year is much better," he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo López said that events like the frosts of the beginning of the year retained the state economy and restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flux is produced by several events, between which the frosts, one of the main effects was a slow economy that does not turn fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level of flow in the trials, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we close much below the expectations we had," he said.
Redefining the vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, President of the Patronial Confederation of the Mexican Republic of Sinaloa said that we want to channel the state towards productive activities of more dynamism.
"In general terms, we have observed that we have worked, we believe it is necessary to develop a long-term programme that redefines the vocation and economic direction of the state, because it is important that we detonate all the potential of Sinaloa's material and human resources," he says.
A lot to do
The President of the Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision of the future that better channels the Government's efforts.
"In general terms, I would say that the Government has made efforts to deliver good results in different areas, in terms of economic development there are some advances, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown advances in the way public policy is managed.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the Government is more inclusive, what I can say is that we have done a lot of work and the Government is aware that there is still a lot to do," he says.
