Court validates "analog cut" in Mexico in 2015
The substitution of analogue signals by digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has suffered in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) has dismissed the constitutional controversies that the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have formulated against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analog cut" from 2021 to 2015, as the eight votes necessary to invalidate it have not been gathered.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when he issued the decree detailing the actions to be taken to make the transition to terrestrial digital television a reality.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic, was rejected for failing to reach a qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality of the decree, and this continues to be in force.
The draft sentence, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed the declaration of the decree as non-constitutional, because the regulation of radio and television is a statutory allocation to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reserve of law.
In favour of the project voted only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero itself.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree and admit complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero has suspended the application of the decree and all the actions planned by it for the digital transition.
The plenary session of the Ministers also decided to reject the complaint made by the Chamber of Deputies, without discussing the draft for which Minister Sánchez Cordero is also responsible.
In his speech, the Minister President said that he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the Federal Executive cannot structure through general standards the measures so that the public administration prepares for it.
"I also consider that it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body", and he recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the Federal Executive, whose constitutional mandate is the management of the state.
The substitution of analogue signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has suffered in recent years and this translates into better radio spectrum operation, better signal quality and more channels.
To postpone the change, he argued, would be to postpone the benefits of digitalization which involves a decision of public interest that not only has a technical dimension, "because it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues".
These issues, he stressed, “require the operation of an entire system, in accordance with the principle of economic direction of the State, encompasses a group of responsibilities which the Constitution grants to the faculty of the State executive”.
He recalled that many countries around the world have already completed the digital transition and they have done so through the Executive, despite the fact that they have highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, in issuing the contested decree, has in one form invaded the sphere of competence of the Congress, because it ensures in the administrative sphere the respect of the laws issued by the Legislative, he assured.
Analysis of the possibility of a vote by vote in Michoacán
According to the data highlighted by PREP, the difference between the first and second place in the governor's election is only 27 per cent, even without counting the votes corresponding to the 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
The possibility of counting "vote by vote" is a reality with regard to the electoral process this year in Michoacán, where according to the data highlighted by the Preliminary Electoral Results Programme (PREP) the difference between the first and second place in the governor's election is only 27 per cent, even without counting the votes corresponding to the 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
In this sense, the President of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on the past 9 November, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines to harmonize local standards with the federal reform in electoral matters.
It will be recalled that Michoacán did not ratify either his Political Constitution or his State Electoral Code or his Electoral Justice Act, at the same time as the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for the entry into force of this electoral process ended and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted its publication within the time limits provided for by the Law of the State Official Gazette, with the argument that he had some objections.
On the same 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the Local Legislative Power and characterized the vote of the state representative for constitutional reforms as "invalid and illegal" because he does not have the right to "sanction or challenge them".
Interviewed about the possibility of "vote by vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal said that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of IEM it will be possible to make partial and total counts of votes by the local electoral body.
Thus, the partial counting of votes, of one or more electoral packages, may be that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there are no voting records and the ballot box file is not counted in the ballot box's file; or there are obvious errors or alterations in the minutes.
In addition, the total count of the votes received in all ballot boxes of the election may be made when there is an indication that the difference between the candidate who is supposed to win the respective election and the candidate who obtained second place in the election is equal to or below a percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express petition from the party representative and/or coalition that submitted the second of the candidates reported.
The total count of the vote may also be carried out if, at the end of the common count, the difference between the supposed winner and the second place candidate is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is an express petition from the representative of the political party whose candidate has come out second, in which case the electoral packages which have been the subject of the partial count will be excluded.
It should be mentioned that this is the situation of the Morelia election, where according to the PREP, the difference between first and second place is only 0.16 percent, even without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
