As a bassist, what are his influences?
There's so many...
Among the first ones I remember were Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many influences, I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I love.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep up the grunge despite the fact that it is no longer fashionable?
I think we all feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I just mentioned, such as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all those who have arisen at the same time and, if it is relevant now, I think it's wonderful, because it's music worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are now doing the best music ever.
At first, his music had a darker content and now it has become more positive.
What is the reason for this change?
It's interesting, because I think there are songs in the new album that seem lighter, but there are also songs, like The End or Just Breathe qualified as very obscure songs, even though these can sound a little positive.
With both, when Ed played them for me, I cried when I listened to them and these are deeply obscure songs.
I think if you grow up and there's a trauma in your life and you lose to a parent or friend, these things start to influence your art and music and these songs, no doubt, represent that to me.
I also think that we can also be happy and even so we can make dark music.
