The Secretariat of Communications and Transport (SCT) has informed that the results shown on the accident in which the Secretary of Government, Francisco Blake Mora and other seven people lost his life, indicate that the helicopter was shocked directly against the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot being able to attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Communications and Transport Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome mentioned that prior to the aircraft's take-off, the pilot found that the weather conditions were adequate for flying.
"The elements that seem to indicate that the unit had various contacts with the ground, the blades had contact with the trees at 25 metres where the unit lost the fuselage".
He also informed that the unit was designed for 19 people, so the unit met the requirements to carry the personnel.
In addition, he said that investigations in the impact area did not report the appearance of pieces on the ground.
"In a search it was reported that there were no parts or components of the aircraft in another location, the impact occurred structurally.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 passengers and met the requirements to carry them.
The soil had a pant of seven to 30 degrees of inclination.
For the time being, the Secretary has assured that a priority is to have the results as quickly as possible; but the investigation can last a few months, it can even last a year.
In turn, Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Airports and Auxiliary Services assured that the moment of impact, the helicopter of the Presidential Major State was operating in cruise speed and this happened on a soft ascending ground.
"This information supports the hypothesis of normal cruiser operation at the time of impact," he says.
During the press conference, the SCT holder, Pérez Jácome, listed six important elements in the investigation:
Visual theft:
According to aeronautical standards, the flight was performed according to visual flight rules, which means that the crew must have visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
Reports in the AICM indicated adequate take-off conditions, and as the aircraft advanced to the border area between DF and the State of Mexico there were layers of shallow cloudiness.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to cloud conditions, the crew searched for a lower height area and more visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
Location of impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the last recording of the aircraft on the radar coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration of the flight path.
Dispersal of aircraft remains in a reduced area:
The information available so far suggests that the impact has occurred on a straight and lateral path.
The dispersion model of the aircraft remains suggests that the helicopter struck the ground under structural integrity conditions.
There were no signs of fire or explosion:
In the location of the disaster there is still no trace in the remains of the aircraft of a type of explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that the aircraft had had multiple contact with the ground.
During the field work, parts of the aircraft were found at a height of 9 mile 200 feet above average sea level, with a slope that has been going from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which he may have disarticulated himself along his journey.
The information provides evidence that suggests that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts with the ground.
After careful search in a wider area than the surrounding location, around the accident, scattered parts of the aircraft were not found, which supports the presumption that the impact occurred under conditions of structural integrity.
MSS announces protocol to find obesity gene
Social Insurance is conducting an investigation to discover the obesity gene for children and youth; this is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting an investigation to discover the obesity gene for children and young people, called the 'Genetics of Childhood and Adolescent Obesity' protocol that will allow to have the markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Biochemistry Medical Investigation Unit of the Specialties Hospital of the National Medical Centre of the 20th Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Investigation and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
In the investigation it is invited to participate the population with or without the right, to present themselves to the participating sports units of the IMSS in Valle de México, where the evidence is carried out to the minors every Saturday from 8:00 hours.
It has emphasized that the protocol began in the Cuauhtemoc Sports Unit (Estado de México Poniente) and that from October 8, the activity takes place in the Sports Unit of Nezahualcóyolt (Estado de México Oriente).
After reaching the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Sportive Independencia Unit (south of Distrito Federal) and finally in the Sportive Morelos Unit (north of Distrito Federal).
He explained that the objective of this investigation and that of knowing the components and the importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the occurrence of chronic degenerative diseases.
As the World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on November 14, he mentioned that the goal is to bring together three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and under the supervision of their parents, for the application of the specific feeding questionnaires.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and their history of family inheritance from their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that on Saturdays anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin, and genetics will be applied to all participants (the identification of people associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that in only six years there was a 77 per cent increase in obesity among boys and 47 per cent among girls; in the case of overweight there was also a dramatic increase', the IMSS specialist pointed out.
He indicated that the rationale for marker research is based on the fact that the country's population is different from others in its genetic history.
He informed that on average, Mexicans have a 65 percent Indo-American heredity, a 30 percent European and a five percent African and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity results in the inability to burn excess energy that is consumed (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to participants is the full assessment of children, which helps to detect whether they have a degree of overweight or obesity.
He even said that the presence of dark-coloured folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicate the probability of suffering metabolic and even pre-diabetes alterations.
The information is managed in a confidential manner, and physicians provide it in writing to parents, who explain each of the measures and changes in their lifestyle to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentaryism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, stay most of the day sitting in front of the TV and use means of transport instead of walking for short distances.
Another cause is the high calorie intake, i.e. the highest consumption of sweet drinks, carbohydrates (tamales - meat pie with corn flour wrapped in corn leaves - bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid blackcurrant
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at UNAM, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the pavement were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200 thousand blackcurrant each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of Valle de México, warns Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher of the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who assured that if the process of building and maintaining the asphalt pavement is adequate, the blackcurrant could be reduced or even eliminated completely.
During his conference A technological opinion on blackcurrants, organized within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera felt that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve yield, and therefore the formation of blackcurrant.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier share of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called malthenes, which together give the pavement its viscoelastic behavior characteristic.
The viscoelastic behaviour of asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, close to 180 degrees, behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very large and at 50 degrees C it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day depending on environmental and temperature conditions, the chemical engineer warns.
The FQ researcher observed that the majority of the streets in Ciudad de México were covered by a flexible pavement, consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Between the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and compacted later.
Each of the small stones that form the layer, he pointed out, is bathed in asphalt.
When vehicles pass through it by generating effort, it allows the forces to spread very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, it would spread better, opinating the chemical ingenuity.
On the asphalt layer, he says, one puts a last layer called a rolling layer, made of fine stone, that is, sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide adhesion in the street.
Being the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the forces, the bearing layer also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material it is made of must be treated.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, because they significantly affect the yield of the asphalt layer.
When the soil gets wet, the water spreads inside the layer is difficult for it to come out, which softens all the layers of the pavement and therefore causes blackcurrants.
In the process of forming a blackcurrant, he says, the first one to spoil is the rolling film and only later is affected the asphalt layer, but the damage does not take place immediately, but it is a process that must be treated at the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National Researcher System explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor for the formation of blackcurrant and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always be linked to the load of vehicles and guarantee its satisfaction, to avoid the frequent formation of blackcurrant.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and make it possible to repair blackcurrants easily and without having to use high temperatures.
