Japan reborn after the earthquake
GDP rises 1.5% due to domestic consumption and ends the downward spiral of early March
Since March the Japanese economy had been paralysed, recovering again after the devastating earthquake that became a nuclear crisis, the worst catastrophe in the Japanese country since World War II.
The first estimates of the Tokyo Government calculated the material losses at $300,000 million, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, seems to have eased.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, the Gross Domestic Product data between July and September were used to turn the page permanently: GDP increased by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and 6% in annualized rates.
The one recorded in the second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year starts in March 2012 - assumes, in addition, the greatest rate of increase since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery is partly due to the resumption of equipment acquisitions to restore the areas devastated by the earthquake and the post-tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the decline of 0.9% of capital expenditure observed from January to March, the first decrease after six months of uninterrupted increase.
However, the real stimulus of the Japanese economy is not based exclusively on the Keynesian impulse that invites us to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - infrastructure, to use deficiencies to grow from zero.
Japan has woken up mainly due to changes in domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japan's GDP.
This variable increased by 1%, driven by higher spending on vehicles, travel and entertainment.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo returned to the internal market when the yen - the Japanese currency - became one of the "refugee values" elected by investors fleeing the debt crisis in the Eurozone and the forecast turmoil of the United States, a privilege that weighs like a slab in the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger division, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic float line is determined by the health of major technology groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, were responsible for their low results between July and September for the yen's contribution.
While markets continue to have their seats in the peripheral EU countries, the Yoshihiko Noda Government does not drop the guard.
"We must follow the risks that persist, such as the deterioration of certain foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen," said yesterday the Secretary of State for Economic Policy, Motohisa Furukawa.
And indeed, the prospects are not at all encouraging.
The Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) mentioned that the majority of member countries presented clearer signals of economic slowdown in September.
The indicator that anticipates the points of inflection of the world economy has highlighted that the main powers are being restrained.
Because it dropped four decimal places to 100.4 points, compared to 100.8 in August.
Eurozone was even below the average, which is in the 100 level, n lowering eight decimal places to 99.13 points.
