"The main task of this government is to implement the decisions of the summit of 26 October," Papadimos said when he opened yesterday a parliamentary debate that will end tomorrow with a vote of confidence for the new Executive.
A package of 24 programmes to boost employment, reform of the disciplinary code for civil servants and new measures against tax evasion will be the first initiatives.
However, Samaras no's message casts doubt on his position: "We have committed ourselves to helping the Transitional Government, but we have committed ourselves to nothing more".
The conservative leader has gone a step further in his pulse than EU and IMF, the agencies that must release the 8,000 million that Athens urgently needs, and has made it clear that he will not approve any letter of commitment to implement the adjustments.
But the European Commission, still irritated by the impact of the whole Papandreu referendum, reiterated yesterday that its demand is firm: it will not release the aid if the new Government and the leaders of the main Hellen parties do not sign "a written commitment without ambiguity as soon as possible".
