Queen Sofía: "These are instruments for progress and hope"
The Queen emphasises the "preponderant" position of Spain with regard to this type of finance
Spain "has reached a world-leading place in the role of Microfinances".
Queen Sofía recalled that in the last two decades the country has become the world's second largest donor to this instrument of cooperation, the essence of which lies in the fact that it is an "instrument for social progress, justice and hope in a better future for all humanity, based on trust in the human being".
The Queen inaugurated yesterday the Fifth World Microcredit Summit in Valladolid with the certainty that "there is no doubt" that this type of operation is "absolutely indispensable" to achieve the Millennium Goals set by the United Nations for 2015, and, "very especially, in that which aims to reduce to half the volume of people living on incomes under one dollar a day, to which is set the "threshold of poverty".
Spain "continues to work" to expand the network of beneficiaries "in every corner of the world, and carries out this task with "responsibility", said Queen Sofía, who hoped that the initiatives and contributions originating during the Summit, which will extend until Thursday, "guarantee the creation of new capacities and better opportunities for the poorest and especially for women", the main beneficiaries of these loans.
We have "achieved many goals" and "we face many challenges".
The Microcredit Summit is seen not only as a forum for debate, but also as the platform from which to push "two basic goals".
Thus, Her Majesty explained that the goal is that by the end of 2015 there are 175 million poor families that have accessed these financial services and that one hundred million of these families are going beyond the poverty line they are now living on.
The impulse in the conception of microcredits in Spain and the rest of the world "followed the path initiated a few years ago in a pioneering way" by Muhammad Yunus, stressed Queen Sofía as an "act of justice and recognition due".
And she described the father of this instrument as an "admirable idealist in the universal cause of the fight against poverty", the work she has known for 15 years, when the Queen travelled to Bangladesh to know about her lending policy on the ground.
This experience was followed a year later by the first World Summit in Washington and other meetings such as those celebrated in Côte d'Ivoire in 1999, Canada in 2006, and "at each meeting I was able to see a continuous evolution", explained Her Majesty, whose relationship with this project brought him yesterday the term "head of the family" meeting in Valladolid from the "banker of the poor".
Finally, Queen Sofía concluded her speech by encouraging those present to participate in the debate and in the search for solutions to move forward in the fight against poverty.
