What is fraud at sick stoppages?
After the allowances, the UMP and the government launch the offensive on sick stoppages.
Nicolas Sarkozy will be in Bordeaux on Tuesday 15 November to visit a family allowance fund, and deliver a speech on the theme - recurring since 2007 - of the fight against social fraud and assistance.
And to accompany this offensive, which starts from a desire to make savings in a context of rigour, but is no less heralding an axis of the presidential campaign to the right, the majority wants to focus on sick stops.
First of all, with a view to saving budgets: the government plans to impose a fourth day of default on employees in the private sector before taking over a stoppage of work.
In short, without a specific company agreement, an employee who falls ill would lose four days' salary, thus at least 15% of his monthly income.
A measure that could provoke anger, but which would yield 280 million euros, according to Les Echos.
And that would be accompanied by another measure, more symbolic in scope: to impose on civil servants a day of non-compensated deficiency in the event of a stoppage of work (they have so far no waiting period, compared to three days in the private sector).
While these issues are under discussion, the majority are also reviving the topic of fraud, this time targeting abuses related to work stoppages.
"The controls will be much more important and, if you are taken, you will pay back," said Xavier Bertrand at RTL's microphone on Sunday, November 13.
As in other cases, the publicity effects seem somewhat disproportionate to the reality of work stoppage fraud.
This has been the subject of constant monitoring and political offensives since 2002, most of which have borne fruit.
The French are no sicker than elsewhere in Europe.
Let us first look at the national figures.
According to the National Health Insurance Fund (CNAM), more than 237 million euros of daily allowances were issued in 2006.
According to the Institute for Research and Documentation in Health Economics, daily allowances in 2008 accounted for 5% of health expenditure, with 11.3 billion euros.
Of this amount, 46% concerned maternity leave and accidents at work, and 54% concerned sick leave, i.e. EUR 6.2 billion.
And so 2.5% of health spending.
In 2010, the French experienced an average of 14.5 days off work, compared to 17.8 days in 2009, according to a study by the Alma Consulting group.
An average that hides some discrepancies: another survey, published in 2007 by the career management website Monster.com, showed that 75% of the 40,000 French employees interviewed said they had taken no sick day.
Another study, this time from Health Insurance, states that in 2010, 37% of sick leave was for less than 8 days, 22% from 8 to 14 days, 15% from 15 days to one month, 15% from one to three months and 11% beyond.
When compared with their European neighbours, French employees are no more likely than elsewhere to stop work.
A long study conducted in 2010 by two CNRS researchers showed that between 1994 and 2001, the overall rate of absence (for health reasons or not) in France varied between 10% and 11%, compared with 20% and 28% in Denmark, 15% in the United Kingdom or 16% and 18% in the Netherlands.
Fraud at sick stoppages represents very little in the face of work in the dark.
As for fraud, it is only a small one.
The strengthening of legislation since 2002 means that checks on sick leave of more than 45 days are systematic.
In 2008, out of 1.5 million checks, CNAM found that 13% of the 285,000 short-term stops were "unjustified or too long", or 37,050 cases.
In the case of detentions of more than 45 days, which were systematically monitored, 11% of 1.2 million cases were "unsuitable or unjustified", or 132 000.
In total, 169,000 "unjustified" cases out of several million employees who have had a sick leave.
A figure which represents very little compared, for example, to that of work in the dark.
According to UMP MEP Dominique Tian, author of a report on the issue in June, it would amount to 9 to 15 billion euros of tax loss per year, which is more than the total cost of daily allowances, and thus infinitely more than fraud against them.
Papademos: Greece will have to implement a new adjustment plan
Greece will need a new adjustment programme to correct its economy.
That is what Prime Minister Lucas Papadémos said to Parliament on Monday 14 November, adding that the 100 days given to his united government would not be enough to accomplish this task.
"To continue economic recovery efforts, we need the support of our European partners and a new fiscal adjustment programme," said the head of government, who was delivering his first public speech at the opening of the debate on the vote of confidence in Parliament on Wednesday.
The implementation of the decisions taken at the euro area summit on 27 October will be the "main task" of the new government, as the country's participation in the euro area "is at stake", he added.
As a result, Mr Papadémos predicted that the country's government deficit would be reduced "to around 9%" of GDP by the end of the year, after having been 10.6% in 2010 and 15.7% in 2009.
Right rejects new austerity measures
Antonis Samaras, the leader of the right, on Monday supported the measures already approved to try to get out of the debt crisis but warned that his party would not commit to additional austerity.
"We will not vote in favour of new measures," he said at a meeting with the deputies of his party, New Democracy.
He agreed with the objectives of reducing the deficit and debt, and combating waste but hostile to any policy that would prevent economic recovery.
To Olli Rehn, the European Commissioner for Economic and Monetary Affairs, who warned that the IMF and the EU would not release the necessary EUR 8 billion loan without a written guarantee from all parties that they would support the planned measures, Antonio Samaras replied that his word was enough and that he would not sign anything under external pressure.
We need to legalize euthanasia and assisted suicide, says a committee of experts
Canadians live in denial of death, according to the Royal Society of Canada report
In the area of palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions, and physicians to work together to ensure better palliative care beyond cancer.
Canadian society lives in denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians agree to talk to their doctor about the conditions in which they want to die and make arrangements to do so.
This is one of the findings of an impressive report by the Royal Society of Canada, in which six experts from a variety of fields, including ethics, law and medicine, participated.
This committee recommends that the government amend the Criminal Code to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, where appropriate, with a patient deemed competent to make such a decision.
At the outset, experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
If Canada ranked 10th, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has generated a culture in which people are afraid to address the subject of death."
Medicalization or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, reports the experts mandated by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the desire of most Canadians to die at home, 68.6% of them eventually die in hospital.
In the country as a whole, this rate is highest in Quebec, with 86% of deaths occurring in hospital.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report come to conclusions that run counter to the position of the federal government, which has already said that it does not want to change anything in the Criminal Code regarding euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who have also reviewed all countries where these approaches are legalized or decriminalized, there is no evidence that this decriminalization leads to abuse in application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or assisted suicide on non-competent or non-consensual persons.
On the contrary, Jocelyn Downie, co-signatory of the report, said yesterday in teleconference, there would be more cases of these spillovers precisely in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized.
"Euthanasia is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal".
"Assisted suicide is practised in Canada, where it is clearly illegal," says Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians in Support of Euthanasia
Recall that 85% of Canadians have already expressed support for euthanasia because they believe it would help end-of-life people alleviate their suffering, according to an Angus Reid poll conducted in 2010.
And 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not send the message that the lives of the elderly or disabled have less value.
As for those who have committed assisted suicide, 41% of the respondents believe that they should not be prosecuted.
The situation with regard to patient retention or cessation of care is less clear, the authors of the report say.
Therefore, in the list of recommendations, they suggest that the Criminal Code states that withdrawal of care for which there has been a legally valid refusal is not criminal.
The Expert Panel also calls for health professionals to be trained in the duty to respect a denial of end-of-life care, without fear of criminal prosecution.
In the area of palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions, and physicians to work together to ensure better palliative care beyond cancer.
Finally, with respect to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the Committee requests that it be considered, when not used to reduce physical pain, as euthanasia, and that it be subject to the same procedures.
Reservations from other experts
Some experts in the field of health law have already expressed reservations about the findings of the Royal Society of Canada Expert Report.
Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, described the position of the experts who signed the report as "extreme", among other things because it does not limit the practice of euthanasia to the terminally ill.
"This opens the door to a situation where anyone who is tired of life and who is over 18 years old could ask for help to commit suicide," said Mr Deschamps, who had consulted yesterday a summary of the report.
Mr Deschamps also points out that the authors of the report seem to place the autonomy of the person above all other values that participate in the social fabric of society.
"In society," he says, "there are beacons and constraints."
Health law specialist Margaret Somerville also expressed "strong opposition" to the report's findings, which she called "pro-euthanasia manifesto".
Margaret Somerville, who herself is a member of the Royal Society of Canada, specifically challenges the report's data on the absence of abuse in some countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legalized, namely the Netherlands and Oregon.
