On Tuesday, the government of the large-scale Social Democratic/Christian Democrat coalition in Austria decided to include in the constitution a budget "gold rule" in order to reduce public deficits and thus avoid a possible deterioration by rating agencies of Austria's sovereign rating (triple A).
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann who announced this decision at the end of a Council of Ministers, while the Austrian public debt was 74.6%, well above the maximum 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty, but well below the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
