Austria thus responds to a request from the Brussels summit of the euro area member countries on 26 October last: the Heads of State and Government had then called for the inclusion by the end of 2012 of the reduction of public deficits and a return to the balance of public accounts in the constitution or in a law of the same value.
The scheme adopted by the Austrian Government is similar to the "German model", since Germany was the first European country to adopt such a "rule".
By 2017, the structural government deficit will have to fall by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year and, as of 2017, the federal government's structural government deficit will not have to exceed 0.35% of GDP each year, while regional states and municipalities will have to present balanced budgets.
The objective is to bring public debt up to 2020/21 under the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty.
