Energy policy:
the facts must prevail over dogmas
If there is one subject which cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or under the influence of emotion, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity have a direct impact on the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is healthy that an election meeting should be an opportunity to reflect on such issues and on the place of nuclear power.
The debate will only be fruitful if it explores the full economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
While we are 7 billion human beings on the planet, demographic change will lead to a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, unless we deprive a huge part of the world's population of a vital element.
At the same time, the scarcity of fossil resources will have to be overcome in order to continue to produce electricity permanently, not to mention the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in order to combat climate disruption, a subject that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not alter any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains isolated in its decision to renounce nuclear power.
This is not the case for Belgium, which is subject to the need to be able to find a replacement source capable of replacing itself, nor for Switzerland, which just wants to build only last generation power plants.
On the other hand, the Czech Republic, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name just a few, are pursuing their projects with determination.
The United States decided after Fukushima to add a unit to their park by resuming the construction of a power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
While the German model, which focuses on renewable energy, is sometimes presented as an example, the reality contradicts the discourse.
Berlin's choice will result in higher electricity prices, increased energy dependence due to the increased use of imported gas, especially from Russia, a surge in CO2 emissions resulting from the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, all these unfortunate effects are already being felt.
The case of Denmark should be considered.
European wind champion, from which he draws 30% of his electricity, he is also one of the largest users of coal and gas due to the intermittency of the wind; as a result, his CO2 emissions and the price of his electricity are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the other hand, thanks to the constancy of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a electricity bill 40% higher than that of French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of the industrial tool on the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
As a result, any significant reduction on the part of nuclear power would lead to a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would make it illusory the beautiful statements on the reindustrialisation of our country and the defence of purchasing power.
A price that a large majority of French people refuse to pay, especially since they do not object in principle to this energy, the polls show it.
It should be recalled that our country's energy policy has made it possible to build an industrial sector of 125,000 direct jobs and 410 000 induced jobs.
Strongly exporting, it brings a galaxy of SMEs specializing in international markets and makes them very creative of non-localized jobs.
If France were to decide to leave nuclear power, it would be to sacrifice many of these SMEs by reducing the annual EUR 6 billion worth of French exports of nuclear equipment and services as a source of grief.
Which electrician would order an EPR designed to operate for sixty years when the decline of its manufacturer would be programmed?
In order to solve the energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no source of miracle electricity generation, nor is there a demonic one.
The development by Areva of low CO2-emitting solutions, both nuclear and renewable, testifies to the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear power, maintaining the highest level of safety is an absolute imperative.
In France, we have a Security Authority that exercises intransigent and transparent control over existing power plants as well as the Flamanville yard.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, are inhabited by the same obsession with safety.
In half a century, the nuclear industry has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, operated under normal operating conditions; it remained without human or environmental consequences.
In Chernobyl, the design of the reactor and unforgivable human faults caused the tragedy.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident is the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude that have caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it did for the previous two.
As a result of this approach and of cooperation between the French and German safety authorities, operators and manufacturers, the EPR presents a concept that makes it capable of resisting such phenomena.
While it is considered by all electricians who want to build a power plant, stopping its construction in Flamanville would be a magnificent gift offered to Areva and EDF's competitors by leaving them the free way to seize leadership in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy mix for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotion, dogma and partisan maneuvers dominate such a decisive debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or a chance for the economy?
The immigration policy conducted under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various angles - congestion of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of the number, compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "human rights countries" of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has come to light, the Minister of the Interior (read Libération of 23 May) proclaiming in passing that France "does not need foreign talent, masons and restaurant waiters".
But it is rarely analysed from an economic point of view.
There is a fairly broad consensus on this subject between the left and the right.
On the right, the tone was set by Jacques Chirac who declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country with nearly 2 million migrant workers", and on the left, by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot accommodate all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, the fear of the invasion of the national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared left and right.
For both sides, immigrants are seen as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that will be given to immigrants.
In his programme, François Hollande confines himself to banalities, indicating that co-development will solve our "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may pay electorally; but it is economically very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent book synthesizing the most recent knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among scholars on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
Restricting immigration anemia growth and hindering employment.
Concerns about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that they may replace national workers, especially the low-skilled, exerting downward pressure on their wages.
However, experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for national employees, mainly engaged in trades in sectors in need of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national employees, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors in which training does not track the supply of jobs.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon will find it difficult to work in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants make the arrivals of immigrants have a positive effect on the wages and employment of nationals.
Giovanni Peri thus calculated that a 1% increase in migration flows results in an increase of between 0.6 and 0.9% in real long-term wages.
And this does not take into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (strong proportion of naturalized immigrants among the American Nobel Prize winners; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems, averaging 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The World Labour Organisation estimates, for example, that in Germany, an immigrant at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (revenue less expenditure) of EUR 150000 to public budgets on average over the whole of his life.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted, at the beginning of his term, to look for the missing growth points "with teeth".
The teeth in question, when used to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, European democracy remains to be thought of
Democracy is a precious good; it is also a fragile good.
The European continent should be able to remember this, which, for having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, has experienced the tragedies of the Great War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the Gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that it would be sufficient for democracy to definitively triumph over its enemies to exercise the vote, and to exercise it in the most direct way possible.
It is known, from Napoleon "The Little One", that this was an easy thought.
Universal suffrage, to be the necessary condition of democracy, is not the sufficient condition and can even become an "instrument of oppression" as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation and control of powers, an education, Enlightenment, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis in Europe that we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is just as much and first of all a crisis of politics and democracy.
The palinodie of the true-false Greek referendum has in this respect had the value of double revealing: that of the need for a powerful return of politics, but also that of the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be thought of to be exceeded.
The truth is that the front lines of democratic combat have now shifted, and that for many of them Republican soldiers are no longer shooting in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain from demanding a succession of national referendums, organized according to necessity and in dispersed order.
A white-seing with the absolute European monarch or a foot jump joined in the vacuum of the nationalist retreat: what a choice for the citizen!
No, we do not want cuts, but we want a common exercise, rightfully, serenely and continuously, of choice and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal - there is no more where to stop enumeration - because there is only one crisis, and it is in Europe.
It is Europe as a whole that bends to the dictates of markets and rating agencies, which suffers from its impotence and its lack of solidarity.
It is Europe as a whole that is humiliated on the international stage.
We are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe - but it is Europe as a whole that is slowly losing its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
The urgency is to restore the leadership of the European project to popular sovereignty.
For it is together that Europeans will be able to reduce the burden of their debts, free themselves from the markets and prepare for the future by investing.
The end of the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, except of course to lead us to disaster.
After a long time of fighting this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone today calls for the European economic government.
All right.
But to think of it without stronger political and democratic integration, and lived as such by the citizens, would be a new madness and a new impasse.
We must take on a new stage in the construction of Europe.
To make the Republic in France, it was necessary to "do" republicans.
The revolution in interests could not be enough.
This lesson remains valid.
We need to build a more economically integrated Europe.
This can only be achieved by building a more democratic Europe at the political level, a genuine European popular sovereignty.
To make Europe, let us make Europeans.
